<section id="fs-id1909383" class="section-summary"><title>Section Summary</title><list id="fs-id2599702">
    <item id="import-auto-id1899657">Kirchhoff’s rules can be used to analyze any circuit, simple or complex.</item>
    <item id="import-auto-id1954890">Kirchhoff’s first rule—the junction rule: The sum of all currents entering a junction must equal the sum of all currents leaving the junction.</item>
    <item id="import-auto-id2670222">Kirchhoff’s second rule—the loop rule: The algebraic sum of changes in potential around any closed circuit path (loop) must be zero.</item>
    <item id="import-auto-id2683482">The two rules are based, respectively, on the laws of conservation of charge and energy.</item>
    <item id="import-auto-id2595427">When calculating potential and current using Kirchhoff’s rules, a set of conventions must be followed for determining the correct signs of various terms.</item>
    <item id="import-auto-id2639010">The simpler series and parallel rules are special cases of Kirchhoff’s rules.</item>
</list>
    </section><section id="fs-id3286336" class="conceptual-questions" type="conceptual-questions">
